No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today refused a request to abolish the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko was convicted under an amendment to the Criminal Code.
The amendment, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned former prime minister, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the motion to reduce the penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for entering into an allegedly unfavourable contract with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, and the convicts "appeal is due to be heard in court in December.
Timoshenko himself described the verdict as political revenge by the regime, and in the West, too, the trial raised suspicions of the court's bias.
The motion to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted, from the criminal code was supported by 147 deputies.
226 votes would have been needed to pass it.
