Beginning of a new era of crisis
France and the rest of Europe in the focus of investors.
On Tuesday, a statistical storm roared through Europe.
The individual states published their GDP figures for the third quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the previous quarter, while Germany and France grew.
But today, the bond market is breaking all records.
Investors are keeping an eye not only on Greece, but also on Spain, France, Austria and other countries.
The statistical offices of Europe, Germany, the Czech Republic and some other European countries published their provisional economic forecasts for the third quarter.
Germany's GDP grew by 0.5%, as expected, and France's by 0.4%.
At the same time, both countries revised their data for the second quarter, in which Germany recorded higher growth than originally expected (growth of 0.3% instead of the forecast 0.1%), while France admitted a slight decline of 0.1% (initial data spoke only of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in the third quarter of this year compared to the previous year.
Compared to the previous quarter, however, the gross domestic product stagnated and, according to the Czech Statistical Office, confirmed the trend of a slowdown in economic performance.
The results are therefore worse than analysts "forecasts.
Key events:
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in the third quarter of this year compared to the previous year, but it stagnated compared to the previous quarter.
According to preliminary and seasonally adjusted data, the German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter.
Across the eurozone and the EU, the economy grew by 0.2 percent between July and September compared with the previous quarter, in line with analysts "expectations.
The Greek economy shrank by 5.2 percent year-on-year.
The yield on its 10-year government bonds climbed to 28.45%.
Yields on Italian and Spanish government bonds rose to critical levels.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium and other countries are also beginning to experience problems...
Czech government bond yields remain below 4%, although the situation in the region is deteriorating.
In Germany, voices are being raised that the ECB should become a creditor of last resort.
