A Fat Child's Menu: It Doesn't Eat Breakfast and Eats Sausage for Dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight, with 9 per cent of pupils and 5 per cent of children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the milieu in which a person grows up and the examples that surround him are for the healthy development of a person.
Sausages are up to half more often on the tables of obese children than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 per cent of the overweight children had chips for dinner on the day before the awareness campaign under the motto "Obesity is no coincidence."
Exercise is not one of the most popular pastimes in families with young children, but it also affects the majority of today's pupils - only 15 per cent said their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted last year towards the end of the school year and surveyed almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the "Obesity is no coincidence" campaign, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diets and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the alarming increase in the number of children who are overweight or even obese.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed said they eat breakfast, breakfast, lunch, dinner five times a day - one of the main requirements for a healthy diet," according to one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relatively small things, such as the family's regular breakfast time, are important for a child's healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the families of students have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone has breakfast on their own.
Worst of all was the finding that one in ten families do not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered to be the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that the families of overweight children are much more likely to consume unhealthy fries.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 per cent)
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed play sports, less than half of their parents do - just 15 percent.
Compose your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own menu based on their appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favourite dishes were many pastries, meat dishes and, of course, desserts.
"What is particularly alarming is the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report of this survey emphasises.
At lunch, the main course, pasta came out on top over poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes at all and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes for lunch was also very low.
Return to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"In the control group of respondents, who completed the questionnaire after completing the educational lecture" Obesity is not a coincidence, "there was in many cases a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating," the results of the project show.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet sodas, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also ticked poultry or fish as the main dish of the day much more often in the questionnaire and were willing to eat fewer dumplings or sweet foods.
Professionals claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In the introductory article on how stylists learn, I was a bit grumpy that it was a bit too much stuff to start with.
I had no idea what was to come.
Lectures by three professionals from the industry, the clothing of problematic figures and a seminar on how things work "on the pitch."
There is worse to come.
The closer we get to the test, the more information and practical tasks await us.
But even if the course takes place every Saturday and Sunday, it is still fully booked.
This time we debated with director Alena (not a single man attends the course) how to dress a woman who does not have an ideally proportioned figure.
And that, after all, is most of us.
Some have a too short neck, others a too boyish figure without neat curves and still others are chubby.
It is up to the stylist to visually conceal broad shoulders, lengthen the neck or conjure up the necessary curves.
We also got tips on how to dress a woman like Jennifer Lopez - with a big bosom, wide hips and narrow waist - pretty and figure-hugging without looking too provocative.
For example, if the difference between waist and hips is so great that the skirt or pants really don't fit, you should get at least one piece made to measure.
You won't regret it, because well-fitting clothes are simply priceless.
You feel much better in a tailored skirt like this than in an off-the-rack one that keeps slipping up and down, sticking out at the waist, etc.
In turn, boyish figures can permit themselves to wear clothing with wrinkles, bulbs, appliqués, embroideries or ruffles.
With this amount of information and figure types, I am glad that I have a whole week to thoroughly go through everything.
And yet I am afraid that, given the homework assigned, it is almost impossible to accomplish.
Each of the students was assigned a celebrity to come up with matching outfits for - daywear and evening gowns.
In doing so, we should take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the respective star and his figure type.
I'm supposed to "dress" Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
Inside, I cheer, because for me personally, this is much better than dressing, say, Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has probably gained a hundred kilos lately (well, that's a bit exaggerated), or even the young Selena Gomez.
The garments are to be cut out of magazines or searched on the Internet, printed out and then edited graphically.
The "mood board," as the whole result is called, is meant to express our very personal style and our relationship to graphic design.
It is very important to also think about the graphic side of styling.
The stylist not only attracts the models physically, but also designs the so-called product page in the journals (according to specific specifications, for example trend handbags, coats, etc.).
Stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about this.
But only on Sunday.
This means that a stylist must have a good overall view.
The Saturday lecture, filled with information about figure types, was spiced up by three visitors from the industry:
by the stylist Jan Pokorný, the fashion designer Jakub Polanka and the fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and that a stylist should be able to exploit this.
And a savvy stylist can work with a single piece of clothing in very different ways.
The magic word is variability.
For example, you can wear a trench coat over jeans, like a T-shirt or coat, but you can also wear it on the naked body, wear heels and wear it as a dress.
Simply roll up the sleeves or the collar and the whole look looks completely different.
"Play with it," he insisted.
But the most important piece of advice I got was this: "First, you need to know the rules perfectly."
"Only then can you hurt them," Jakub said.
It finally dawns on me why we have to tick all these boxes, what can be combined with what, and why, even if you often see something completely different in fashion magazines.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to the photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist must have prepared many more clothing variations than he ultimately photographs.
So you have to be prepared to style at least fifteen for a ten-page fashion story (i.e. ten outfits).
And also that the clothing in the photo in combination with other accessories sometimes looks completely different than in reality.
So you have to take all of this into account when designing the outfit.
Jan Pokorný also confirmed that image and style sometimes account for half of the success.
Just look at Madonna, a not-so-brilliant singer whose image and marketing have made her a global star.
In the Czech Republic, the services of a stylist are rather reserved.
Even famous people often think of this as money thrown out (the main thing is that I bring something, how I look is secondary).
And if one of us already has a style, then we should expect that he or she will most likely force a very different (smaller) size on us than he or she actually needs.
Then you only have to google afterwards to find with certainty that the tabloid press writes that the corresponding celebrity has gained or lost weight again, and so on.
On Sunday, Jan and Mario urged us not to believe that a stylist only needs to focus on fashion and then "assemble" the outfit.
In his work he has to communicate with the people he styles and he has to be a clever psychologist.
Evaluate people without pandering to them and standing by their opinions.
'If any manager orders us to sift through her wardrobe and add pretty pieces, we can't sort her out the whole wardrobe and say - my God, that's terrible. '
"You have to find at least a few commendable things to recommend what you can wear," Mario says.
He also showed us in very concrete terms what a so-called "placebo" must contain.
In other words, a bag that is buttoned at the waist and in which you carry all the necessary proprietorships with you.
In addition to such clear items as scissors, hair removal dispensers or safety pins, it also contains such utensils as a nylon thread (this helps the stylist take photos of products such as handbags or hats), special clips that can be used to pull the clothes back in case they are too large (pins or other clamps are prohibited to prevent the fabric from breaking) and, of course, sewing equipment.
So that we not only have to listen, but also try something practical, we learned how to stick shoes properly.
Even when photographing in the studio, where the floor is level, you can damage the sole of the shoe, let alone the outside.
We were glued and glued...
You are not even allowed to touch the shoes with the scissors, so as not to damage them.
So you have to be really skilful.
Mario delighted me by unreservedly praising my "creation."
The aforementioned skill is not exactly my strength.
All this was only a fraction of what we heard at the second weekend continuation course.
One thing has now become clear to me - dedicating yourself to styling at a professional level is not child's play.
V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America

A series of entirely avoidable, amateurish mistakes turn what was originally a carefree ride into a routine early shift.
It was possible to fulfil a large part of the ambitions, but what use is that if no one was obviously in the mood to do a little more.
Even before it hit the shelves, the new part, subtitled "The Run," aroused high expectations.
He promised to take the old game series "Need for Speed" back to a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples it seemed to be more than just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious to see how the adapted passages, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot, turned out.
But as one is used to with NFS, in the end a lot is different than one had expected.
Sure - potentially they're pretty decent arcade races, but overall the game is diminished by some unnecessary mistakes that have been more or less present in this series for a couple of years.
So these are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For starters, you are introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to take part in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the West Coast, you get behind the wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One does not for a moment feel that game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are also very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not exceed that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing earth-shattering.
But the drive through the desert, through autumn landscape or high up through deeply snowy landscape seems visually very pleasant.
Every now and then, untypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be very careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are built in quite well one after the other.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you can expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And in addition, the police get involved, who want to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (actually only three).
In the end, this is rather to the advantage of the game, because this element has at least no chance of becoming boring - it belongs in the context of the above to the elements, which make the game more varied.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is to say, from today's point of view, it does not uproot trees, but on the other hand, one could not say that it is bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model continues to do justice to an action-packed race, although you could find better ones in the competition.
Until then, everything is fine.
Real problems only emerge after some time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
A game of this kind is hardly to be expected to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea how the car behaves before hitting any object, then obviously not everything is in order.
Typical example: when overtaking or passing oncoming cars, you only "touch" the other car slightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations, you go skidding and do wild pirouettes.
Or drive the cart straight to scrap metal.
Thanks to the restart system, this does not matter, but it is annoying from time to time.
The restarts are solved like this: if you have total damage or land far off the track, the game throws you back to the last clue of the track.
Except - in every race you only have five restarts.
When you have exhausted them, everything starts all over again.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn't work out, but you better not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, even the restart does not help, there is nothing else that helps than to learn the critical section from the head.
What is particularly unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, have to be driven through in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Elsewhere, you will always find "civilian" cars in the same configuration, whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see that the opponent in front of you easily passes two oncoming cars, but by the time you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that this situation always happens right under your nose.
The opponents have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent in the same place and again without regard to the time.
The craziest part of this is at the end of the game on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to overtake you here on the devil come out.
And if he is already in front of you, then of course he takes your view, so that at the beginning you drive your own car a few times in lumps.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses the joy of the game.
And that's a pity, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and in places so action-packed that you almost don't know where your head is.
And in principle it does not matter what is "to blame" for it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in such a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
Changing cars during the races is also an unusual idea.
One must not overlook the gas stations along the route, because it is here that one can change the car, although in most cases the car that one has is sufficient.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American sedans for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example on the hairpin bends in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game story is also the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual locations that you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals to be won, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to get to the higher driver level, different objects have to be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also connected to the online autolog function, which, among other things, compares your own results with those of other players and also provides other collective functions.
One of the more incomprehensible carvers is a situation in the last race in history.
Here you come by car into a subway tunnel (because of me), where you race along the rails in the dark (because of me).
Numbers between 150 and 200 km / h look on the speedometer (because of me), but suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives you uncompromisingly to scrap metal.
In our editorial office we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think us so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
All the more annoying is that with some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and sometimes quite dramatically.
However, this applies in particular to accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
Sound reproduction is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as wide a range of rather young audiences as possible, a soundtrack a lá "something from everyone" was created - but who buys such a game just because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? Feelings are rather mixed.
If the game were not diminished by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned above, we could have asserted with the breasttone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But somehow the game seems unfinished.
A great pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared for these mistakes to strike you in the eye with the power of airport spotlights.
Concert of the "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with singing ensembles of Charles University
For the third time, the Festa Academica festival offers the amalgamation of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, along with a musical experience.
In the course of the festival, about twenty professional and university choirs will present themselves.
The focus of the festival will be on the two concerts, which will take place on 17 November.
"Charles University is very involved in the festival."
"The choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and the Faculty of Humanities studies is represented among the participants, and the rector, Václav Hampl, is a member of the festival committee," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organizing team.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of technical school choirs, which will take place on 17 November from 14: 00 on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition "Celebration Jazz Mass" by the famous Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička.
In the evenings, the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty sametu) takes place in the gala rooms of the Folk House in Vinohrady, with university choirs also performing, not excluding choirs from Charles University.
Festa Academica's aim is not only to celebrate World Students "Day in a dignified manner and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music at the highest level to the public and to promote creative cooperation among young people.
The main organizer is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
The event was held under the auspices of Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague and Václav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to festive concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happenings, matinees and other events.
Interested parties can find detailed information on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
Ambassador Vicenová:
The Czechs have a reputation as negativists and eurosceptics
"The Lisbon Treaty has noticeably unbalanced the balance between the individual institutions."
I didn't expect such a hard war to break out. '
"It will take five or six years for the waves to calm down and for everyone to get used to their new role," began Milena Vicenová, the Czech Ambassador to the European Union, quite sharply in her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
She showed how seriously she takes the motto "Understandable and open about Europe" in the first part of her lecture, in which she managed to describe the individual institutions of the EU and their mutual relations in such a clear and comprehensible way that many lecturers in the law faculty of Charles University would have envied her.
Ms Vicenová also praised the new Permanent President of the Council of Europe, Herman Van Rompuy:
"Initially there was criticism that he was too inconspicuous - a grey civil servant who was not up to such a role, but I have to say that it took everyone's breath away how well he handled the matter.
"He is a man who manages to listen patiently to twenty-seven member states, to communicate with them and, above all, to have clear ideas about how the EU should proceed.
She then explained the new position of the High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy as an answer to the question "Who is this - the European Union? Which number should I call?," i.e. as an important step towards the agreement and better readability of EU policy towards states such as China or India.
No one wants to ban us from owning our oil hats
Mrs Vicenová also devoted herself to the agenda according to which the European Union has lived, is living and intends to live in the near future.
She described the Czech Presidency of two years ago as a success.
The Czechs had overcome the financial crisis and the gas crisis and had also organised the Eastern Partnership Summit.
She described the case of the government during the Presidency as a great negative, which had greatly damaged the image of the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU currently has its hands full.
In the Ambassador's words, things were pretty hectic, not only in the Presidency, but also in the ensuing crisis, which has not yet been resolved.
The EU's seven-year budget still has to be approved, which makes things much more complicated precisely because of the current economic situation.
Whether it will be a lean and frugal budget, which sectors of the economy will be given priority, which countries will receive more and which less - all this is now on the agenda.
The Ambassador also recalls her own slogans when she came to Brussels: "Understandable about Europe."
"If I don't like something, it's greyish abbreviations, foreign words and technical jargon that no one understands.
As a citizen, how am I supposed to know whether people in Brussels really come up with crooked or round cucumbers and bananas of different sizes, or whether someone actually wants to ban us from using curds.
It would also have liked to use EU soil to get more Czechs into European institutions.
The prospect of a two-speed or multi-speed Europe
According to the EU ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation for being Eurosceptics who perceive the negative rather than the positive sides of the matter.
This makes the weak representation of Czechs in European institutions all the more galling.
Many factors are to blame for this, including the reluctance of our candidates, their inability to write letters of motivation and, last but not least, the weak support of the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she also highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group, the so-called V4.
"Believe me, when a Pole or Hungarian comes to me and a Slovak is nearby, the Frenchman next to me says:" Hey, what are you putting your heads together - is that your V4 again? "and it makes a pretty sour face.
According to Ms Vicenové, the EU expects, above all, tough rules for the budget policies of the member states in the future.
It regards the concept of a two-speed or even multi-speed Europe as much more real than a "European federation."
"We have here the countries of the euro zone and the countries outside the euro zone.
"We have the Schengen area and we already have the institute of strengthened cooperation."
'For the first time, it has been said that only those countries that want it should work together and those that don't want it should quietly stand aside. '
"There will be more and more such institutions, which will ultimately lead to a strong" multi-speed Europe, "" Ms Vicenová expects.
In this regard, she also appreciated the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in enforcing the principle that all issues affecting the entire EU must be discussed by all member states, not just the eurozone countries.
Brand Story:
The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you were looking for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM's strategy, it would probably be the word "longevity."
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with a technological revolution, known as a modern company, although a century has passed since its inception.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by its first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already advocated that countless global problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the trademark around which the life of the future giant would unfold (and at the same time the title of the company's in-house magazine, which IBM began publishing as early as 1935).
This was also the basis of the corporate culture thoroughly prepared by Watsen.
"For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and succeeded for a century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society in the course of our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the next hundred years, "said Samuel J. Palmisano, the current director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Sophisticated system
Watson was already providing social care for its employees in the 1930s - in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: IBM employees were one of the first American employees to have paid holidays, insurance from the entrepreneur, plus elegant uniforms as work clothes, and a well thought-out remuneration system for the best innovators and traders.
IBM's long-term relationships with its customers are just as sophisticated.
The company was brilliant at promoting talent from the very beginning - IBM was one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
Also in line with this anti-discrimination strategy is the current plan to replace Palmisan at the top of IBM next year with a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years and has previously held the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been conducting so-called online brainstorming sessions, from which many future strategies and innovations arise.
No wonder - there are plenty of ideas, as the company employs almost half a million people.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unshakeable position in the business guarantees the company a strong image both internally and externally.
"From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Rosabeth Moss Kanter, a Harvard Business School professor and author of a book on IBM.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology," added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself points out, there is a difference between merely being present in the market or shaping it directly through this presence.
IBM - known as "Big Blue" in the United States because of its logo - has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies in the world - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services across an incredible range of products, from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM holds the most patents, and five of its employees have already won the Nobel Prize.
His best-known inventions include ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes and the floppy disk.
With about $220 billion in market value (market capitalization), IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (just behind Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the tastes of today's customers - unhappy were, for example, the attempt with the own operating system OS / 2, the online service Prodigy or the computers IBM PC jr.
"Business is about moving forward, so you can't be emotionally tied to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
So IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms - and if they don't work, leave them.
In contrast to the rival Microsoft, which basically stands or falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
Services make up the bulk of IBM's profits, with software and hardware accounting for one-fifth each.
As recently as 1990, hardware was the most strongly represented with a share of more than fifty percent.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-profit assets, while at the same time investing $58 billion in purchasing promising technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues even after 2008, when the modern financial crisis first swept the world like a storm.
Here, too, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first chief executive, Thomas J. Watson, who increased its investment in the midst of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that IBM has emerged unscathed from today's crisis.
The value of IBM shares has rocketed by 120 per cent since 2008, and the company's net profit is growing steadily.
IBM's corporate slogan is: Everything can be changed - only the values cannot be changed.
That is another reason why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also master the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flights
IBM (International Business Machines), founded a hundred years ago in New York, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It only took over the name IBM in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a subsidiary in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history goes back to the eighties of the 19th century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous smart card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired the chief executive of the rival company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
This leader even eclipsed the founders of IBM - the invincible culture and identity of the company is based on Watson's ideas to this day.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began manufacturing and distributing all kinds of machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese slicers to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to $9 million, and the company gradually expanded to every continent.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM engineers and computers helped NASA guide flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, the famous human flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers with the same architecture - the IBM System / 360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of that time, was introduced in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thereby fully entering the high-value consulting and services business.
The strategy that has paid off for IBM over the past three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet."
It represents the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even previously planned, for example to improve the situation in transport and urban management.
In the retail sector, IBM recently launched the "Smarter Commerce" platform to help merchants manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM established a subsidiary in what was then Czechoslovakia - the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Headquarters is located in Prague and is also home to a world-class team of researchers working on voice recognition technology.
