Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies sold mainly trips to the socialist countries of the Eastern Bloc, whereas only the chosen ones were allowed to go to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a ČSSR citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he would need a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel would not be possible.
Even back then, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge queues or spend the night in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even that was far from the end of the story.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge - the condition for leaving for the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
After all, the Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange commitment.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought innumerable weekend houses and dachas - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution by the Czechs.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
An enormous paradox, of which we are no longer aware, is the fact that until 1989 it was impossible to travel to Croatia, currently the most popular holiday destination for the Czechs, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation to neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, causing a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
For a long time, the Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West; everyone wanted to be there at least for a few days.
When travelling to Paris, Czech holidaymakers slept in tents in the park, because who would have had the money for an accommodation in a hotel or a guesthouse at that time?
A typical feature of Czechs travelling abroad at that time was a trunk full of canned goods, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living, and therefore average salaries, increased, leading to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare trips by charter flights after 1997, which made air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past, thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, already had currency-free payments with all the advanced countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - Thailand - was launched.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to sunny countries far away every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations have been flown directly from the Czech Republic.
About 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the USA abolished visa requirements for Czech tourists, which definitely placed our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in their history, Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday, including costs at the resort.
The Annual General Meeting is supposed to find a new chairman - again a stalemate threatens.
Czech football has not had a chairman for almost five months and the threat is that Ivan Hašek's successor at the helm of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not even be known after the extraordinary general meeting in Nymburk on Thursday.
As yet, there is no agreement on the electoral rules under which elections are to be held.
And without them, there can be no vote at all on the three potential successors.
Three interested parties want to manage Czech football - Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
In June, Hašek resigned from his position, calling on his colleagues to unite and find a strong personality who could lead football in the future.
Only - in the era after Hašek, the old quarrels between the two chambers of the association, which could not agree on a common candidate, broke out again.
This became very clear on 16 September, when the new chairman was to be chosen.
The delegates of the General Assembly came to the People's House in the Prague district of Smíchov for free, because the negotiations did not lead to any result and it was not only about the election itself.
It was not even possible to agree on who actually has the right to vote at the plenary meeting - only the statutory representatives or the functionaries with power of attorney.
Agreement was reached, at least in part, on this single point, which was also helped by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, whose opinion was that representation on a power of attorney was not permissible.
However, disputes over electoral rules continue.
Nor did the Executive Committee shed any more light on the matter, at whose meetings - whether ordinary or extraordinary - there is, in principle, nothing else on the agenda at all.
Even if views on the election changed a few times, the key point remained the same.
The question is: how to proceed in the third round to avoid a stalemate?
"The point of contention is whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes or whether a completely different model should be found," stated Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-chairmen of FAČR, who represents professional football in management.
According to the statutory model, the winner in the third round is the candidate with the highest percentage of support in the chamber for which he is running.
Moravia is reportedly prepared to accept the compromise that the winner will be the candidate who receives the higher number of votes from both chambers.
The Czech side, on the other hand, insists on the condition that the winner receives at least a two-thirds majority in this percentage vote count.
"Then the two preliminary rounds will have no meaning at all, this mode would call into question the entire bicameral concept," Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, which would find it best not to bend the electoral rules, but to vote according to the valid statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomáš Paclík agrees with this, even though it appears that of all the candidates, the statutory electoral rules are the most likely to suit Pelta.
"My wish is that as far as possible the election will be in accordance with the statutes."
"So that no nonsensical alternatives are devised, as at the last general meeting," declared the owner (of the football club) Victoria Plzeň, who is a candidate for the first time and who distinguished himself from Pelta in his statements.
But Pelta remains optimistic.
In his opinion, the new chairman will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will cooperate constructively in the future.
'The national team's possible qualification for the European Championship today would certainly help calm tempers. '
"When football rides the euphoric wave, the willingness to cooperate is greater," says the official from Jablonec, who brings the greatest experience of all three adepts, both on a professional and regional level.
Rajchl is more reserved.
"I hope for an agreement, but the situation is unfortunately ambiguous."
"This is not a matter between the people of Bohemia and Moravia, but there is some effort to" adjust "the regulations for their own purposes."
'That's why another blockage at the AGM is not out of the question. '
"I hope, however, that common sense will ultimately prevail," Rajchl said.
But there is not much time left for all sides to come to an agreement.
Some negotiations were supposed to take place directly in Montenegro, but who knows whether the football generality will be complete by the time the qualifiers are played.
The charter plane with which, among others, Dalibor Kučera and Rajchl were to fly to Podgorice could not take off at all in the morning in Prague due to a technical malfunction, and so they feverishly searched for a replacement variant, how to bring a part of the Executive Committee to the venue of the barrage game after all.
In the end, the meeting at ministerial level, which is supposed to take place on Wednesday, will probably be decisive.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Physical Education, would have liked to bring the divided parties within the country's largest sports federation to an agreement.
The stakes are high: state subsidies, the credibility of Czech football and also the forthcoming general meeting of ČSTV, which is supposed to show Czech sport the new direction after the financial problems of Sazka.
Paclík goes into the fight for the position of chairman because he does not see a suitable candidate
If Tomáš Paclík, the head of the Pilsen Footballers "Association, had been able to identify a strong candidate before the extraordinary general meeting, who would have fulfilled all his expectations about the new chairman of the Football Association of the Czech Republic (FAČR), he would not have engaged in the fight for this top position at all.
'If there was a good candidate, I'd fight for him and not vote for him. '
"But in the current situation it was not possible to find such an adept," said Paclík ČTK.
The main reason for Paclík to enter the duel with Miroslav Pelta and Jindřich Rajchl is to prevent the alleged favourite of the election, Pelta, from reaching the top of the FAČR.
Paclík also stresses that, if he wins, he intends to serve as chairman for only one year, i.e. until 2013, the date of the Annual General Meeting.
In the position of chairman, he would like to see an experienced top manager who is not too involved in football.
'I've spoken to some of the people in question personally. '
'It's hard to believe some people told me they didn't want to identify with Czech football at the moment.
"Such views would have been welcome to change," he said.
Most of all, Paclík is said to be disturbed by Pelta's association with the chairman of the Pilsen District Football Association Roman Berbr, a man with a controversial reputation who is regarded behind the scenes as a powerful lobbyist with the ability to influence delegate votes at general meetings.
For this reason, it is unacceptable for Pelta to hold the position of chairman.
'If he wins, it would preserve the status quo and it wouldn't happen in Czech football at all. '
"The support of Berbr, a clever businessman, would be doubly bad for football," Paclík stressed.
He also alludes to the fact that Pelta's name came up some time ago in connection with phone tapping investigations into a corruption affair, from which Pelta emerged with impunity.
'I don't know what prestige a Pelta win would bring to (football). '
"And how would we stand in the eyes of UEFA and FIFA," said Paclík, who is a little more relaxed about his earlier statement that he would sell the Pilsen football club if Pelta became president.
Should Pacquiao win in Thursday's election, however, he could well envision working with Pelta in the future.
So does another candidate - Rajchl, whom Paclík supported before the October AGM, which ended in a fiasco.
'He (Pelta) would be the first one I'd go to. '
'He's got great ability. '
'I'd like to think of him as head of the national team, for example. '
'But I don't think he's capable of running the FA as a manager. '
"I don't stick my nose into things that I don't understand," said Paclík, who caused a stir in September by leading the dismissal of the referees "commission with Luďěk Macela, who was replaced by Dagmar Damková.
Paclík himself claims that he is equal to the role of the president of the association.
Citing his skills in managing private companies, he has also been the boss of Pilsen since last summer, which celebrated its first league triumph with his support in May.
'I've got the power to make a difference in the football environment and contribute to a certain cultivation of that. '
"In order to limit the influence of certain interest groups, which tend to influence disciplinary and appeal committees, which degenerates into unsavoury situations," said Paclík, who makes no secret of his antipathy towards, for example, Sparta boss Daniel Křetínský.
One of his priorities would be to strengthen relations between the FAČR and the Czech Olympic Committee, with the help of which he would lobby political leaders for more money from the lottery tax to be channelled into sport.
'That's one of the key things the new chairman should be looking at. '
"When it comes to taxing gambling, as the political parties say, I understand their reasoning, but they also need to be very clear about where the money is going," he said.
Paclík does not regard his association with the Pilsen Club as a handicap either, although he stresses that the FAČR chairman must be "non-partisan."
Pelta in turn is connected with Jablonec, Rajchl with the Prague Dukla.
'It's not ideal. '
"It does not make much sense to me, however, to hypocritically transfer my shares in the Pilsen Club to a third party in order to return after a year and a half," Paclík clarified.
Pelta promised new FAČR bylaws that would prevent a stalemate in the future.
Two days before the general meeting of the Football Association, one of the candidates for the presidency, Miroslav Pelta, promised that, if elected, he would campaign for the FAČR to be given new statutes that would rule out disputes over the electoral rules in the future.
The official from Jablonec is confident ahead of Thursday's hearing in Nymburk and believes the campaign will certainly be defused if the Czech selection is successful.
Pelta had promised even before the unrealized election in September that if elected, he would focus on the national team and raising funds.
He decided only at the last moment to take part in the election before the last general meeting, so the two-month break might help him defend his ideas about running football and present them in a broader context.
'People at all levels are dedicated to football, they're impatient, so they expect the chairman to be known on Thursday. '
"He feels that it is high time for the association to be run by someone," says the man, who is mainly associated with the Jablonec club, but who also worked for many years at Sparta and on the executive committee.
That is another reason why he believes he has sufficient experience to lead Czech football.
He is convinced that the euphoria that prevailed at the time of Ivan Hašek is responsible for today's problems with the election.
"Unfortunately, at the Annual General Meeting in June, articles of association were approved that were not as perfect as everyone had assumed.
If they hadn't allowed different interpretations, we would have had a chairman by September, "Pelta said.
He used the revision of the most important document of the civic association as a lure for the delegates.
'If I become chairman, I'll take it personally and be ready to take personal responsibility if it doesn't work out. '
"It's a matter of principle, he can't be without it," Pelta said.
Furthermore, he does not try to differentiate himself from his opponents.
He had already announced earlier that he could envisage working with Jindřich Rajchl, whom he recognizes for his legal education, and he knows well that his opponent would be his first deputy.
He also did not attack Tomáš Paclík for a long time, who again did not leave a dry thread on Pelta.
He's been in football for over a year and he's already had some success. '
'But his attacks were disparaging and a lot of people were shocked by his campaign, 'she said.
"This is another reason why many now doubt his real character," Pelta told his opponent, who seems to be true to the proclamations he made back in September.
