Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pools with a UFO look, state-of-the-art pools in Budapest: Those who travel through Europe can experience their blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike, relax their tired legs in whirlpools.
A book shows where wellness in water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past year and a half, one thing was not to be missed in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying backwards on the water, she looked up into artfully designed domes, swam towards marble cherubs waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marvelled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she quickly wrote it down in her notebook - along with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
Architectural historian Meder explored more than 200 swimming pools in this way - and now introduces them in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe" took her through 13 countries: in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sport, says Meder - it's just different in the water.
It is annoying that swimming fans have to put up with blue tiles and the stench of chlorine, while joggers can breathe in the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to the cheerful chirping of birds in the park.
"I asked myself one day why swimming pools always have to be so ugly," says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splashing in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are catered for, according to Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real treat for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, bathrooms have a surface of water."
"On the one hand it is transparent, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" (bathing pleasures) conveys interesting facts about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all, it makes you want to take a leap into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to splendid spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found nitrate-containing waters in a rustic karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath, the basins of which are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, are offered by many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: while the entire city can be seen from Zurich's rooftop pool, the outdoor pool of a swimming pool in St. Anton offers views of the snow-capped Arlberg - and: in the steam bath, there is a window from which you can watch the goings-on on on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most unusual pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
In winter, it steams from three open-top shells, while the mountains of the Ötztal valley rise into the sky in the background.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool did the pool collector Meder get the smell of chlorine in his nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba there is such a strong smell of heating oil that it is hard to believe you have ended up in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen-carbonate-containing medicinal water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to the skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
But there was one place where Iris Meder was disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing area in Luhatschowitz, Czech Republic, she found a cordoned-off area.
The bath, designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has since been closed.
When Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red, white and yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
The decay, on the other hand, was counteracted in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This bath has already been built in three phases; one can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating back to the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, added around 1900.
Since its careful modernisation in 1995, Palais Thermal has been the favourite pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because she originally hails from the Black Forest.
"It is quite an achievement to merge such different building styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace, the dive in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
Agricultural speculation
Deutsche Bank lets commodities business shine through
By Christian Teevs
Is Deutsche Bank abandoning its agricultural commodities business?
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, Josef Ackermann has commissioned a working group to examine the consequences of speculation for the world's poor.
Then, in January, the CEO wants to draw conclusions.

For German citizens, the situation is clear: according to a study, 84 percent of Germans find it unacceptable for banks to speculate on agricultural commodities such as wheat or maize.
Two-thirds of those surveyed even want Deutsche Bank and other credit institutions to withdraw from this business because it exacerbates the problems of the world's poorest.
This is the result of a Forsa survey commissioned by the consumer organisation Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October.
In it, the author Harald Schumann shows that bets on global commodity exchanges drive up prices - and that the banks are therefore partly to blame for the global hunger problem.
The campaign of consumer advocates is specifically directed against Deutsche Bank CEO Josef Ackermann, even if major banks such as Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley act similarly.
Commodity bets were originally intended to hedge traders against price fluctuations.
But most experts now agree that gamblers have decoupled from supply and demand - and are profiting at the expense of the poorest.
Unlike its US competitors, Ackermann responded to the criticism by promising to investigate the allegations and saying that no deal was "worth risking Deutsche Bank's reputation."
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, an international working group is currently examining the allegations in the Foodwatch report.
The audit is expected to be completed by the end of the year, when the results will be presented to the Executive Board of Deutsche Bank - along with recommendations on how to deal with them.
At the end of January, the head of the bank will announce the consequences.
The end result could be a reduction of the commodities business, or even a complete abandonment.
Ackermann tinkering with his image
Foodwatch chief executive Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but reiterated his criticism of the financial industry: "Betting on rising food prices is a stark reminder of how recklessly banks are damaging the public good today."
Ackermann now has a special duty as the top banking lobbyist.
"Deutsche Bank must remove all assets from its portfolio that use money to bet on food prices," Bode said.
"It does not matter whether Mr Ackermann is concerned about people suffering from hunger or the reputation of Deutsche Bank."
Ackermann's insight comes as a surprise at first glance, but it is clear that the Group CEO wants to present a perfect picture just a few months before he leaves office.
Deutsche Bank announced on Monday that the CEO will not join the Supervisory Board as planned.
By moving away from the controversial agricultural speculation, he could improve his image.
And he hardly needs to worry about potential losses - his successor would have to deal with that after all.
One in two would quit commodity investments
Foodwatch is trying to keep the pressure on the manager high.
So far, more than 30,000 internet users have taken part in the organisation's campaign.
On Tuesday, Bode published the survey for which the Forsa Institute surveyed 1,001 people on 7 and 8 November.
Just eleven percent therefore consider it legitimate for Deutsche Bank to offer investments that bet on food prices.
Many bank customers would also draw personal consequences if they learned that their bank participates in such transactions: According to the survey, one in two would terminate all investments in which money flows into commodity speculation.
Forty-three percent would discourage acquaintances from such a bank, and 49 percent said they would consider canceling their account and switching to another institution.
21er Haus in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy endings: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and decayed.
Now it is being reopened as an exhibition centre.
If one raves about modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold curves and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion designed by architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World Exposition is an apt and famous example.
s pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built Austria's pavilion at the next World's Fair.
In 1973 he finally became internationally famous with his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus a bowl-like annex in Munich.
The pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected in the Swiss Garden near Vienna's Südbahnhof station after the World Exhibition, rebuilt and opened in 1962 as a museum of the 20th century - it was called the "20er Haus."
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has stood empty and come down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the building belongs, will open its first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, pushed through the new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, an art historian with a doctorate and a considerable career as a figure skater in her youth, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, pushed through the renovation with politicians and conservationists, raised public funds and private sponsorship money and determined its use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookshop, and an office building was to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology and the pavilion was an "enormously important place" for him, where he had viewed the exhibitions "almost every weekend."
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness upon its transfer to Vienna and its conversion.
There were far bigger problems with the current conversion: the building was "an energy extractor," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Refrigeration bridge steel girders have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements provided space for the new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the street provides the lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown anti-rust colour.
And the cinema hall is exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that was good and cheap and also pleased the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz said recently, a typical "drop-in-the-city story."
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken a real consciousness."
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban stroke of luck has occurred: the completely new "Hauptbahnhofsquartier," with office and residential buildings, is currently being built around the Schweizer Garten.
And another stroke of luck may yet occur: the 21er Haus could be reinforced by another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporäre Kunsthalle, and it is rumoured that she is already negotiating with the city for a neighbouring location in the Schweizer Garten.
