The bank did not admit guilt in the settlement.
That includes Citigroup, which agreed to pay $20.5 million.
NCUA chair Debbie Matz welcomed the concessions from the two money houses.
The National Credit Union Administration (NCUA) is responsible for US cooperative banks and steps in when they fail to protect customer deposits.
The NCUA is trying to get compensation for the multi-billion dollar damage caused.
The current settlements are the first of their kind.
The regulator had also reached out to other big banks, suing JPMorgan Chase, Royal Bank of Scotland and Goldman Sachs over the summer.
