The scandal bank of Lake Zurich
Europe's most adventurous bank is not based in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt in the financial crisis and has been sliding from one crisis to the next ever since.
Now a German is to judge it.
Axel Weber certainly did not think so.
After his spectacular departure from the head of the Bundesbank, it was announced in July that he would take up an almost equally spectacular new job in 2013: Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Swiss major bank UBS - an unexpected and lucrative career step.
Axel Weber publicly rejoiced, praised Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newfound solidity, and dropped friendly remarks about future colleagues.
"UBS has made the turnaround."
"I am looking forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel."
By September, however, it was clear that everything was going to be very different.
A trader at UBS in London had bypassed all of the bank's hedging systems and gambled away around 1.7 billion euros.
UBS CEO Oswald Grübel, a banker renowned not only in Switzerland, had to go.
The Chairman of the Board of Directors of UBS has since also been regarded as weak - and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally arrive?
It has already been announced that Weber will be able to advise the Bank from February 2012 onwards.
And he will take over as chairman of the board as early as May - not just in 2013, the bank said on Tuesday.
It's going to be tough for Axel Weber.
He is not a banker, but an economics professor and central banker, and would certainly have needed some familiarization.
At a stroke, he then assumes responsibility for the strategy of a bank that has just once again proved that it has long since earned the title of "Europe's biggest scandal bank."
On the one hand, UBS is huge - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and on the other, it has been sliding from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once-proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of a secretive and solid, but also sophisticated Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she wanted to become a major player in investment banking as well.
In 2007, for example, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more money from wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
On the other hand, as an investment bank, it had advanced into the league of the world's largest banks.
It made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later long-time banking professor in Zurich, says: "I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank."
"From today's point of view, one wonders: How could I have been so wrong?"
He was terribly wrong.
It was first revealed in 2007 that something was seriously wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli, who had previously been regarded as a highly intellectual and equally ingenious banker, surprisingly resigned.
A few months later, you could see why he had left.
The bank's investment arm had gambled on subprime securities and had to write off billions.
In order to shoulder this burden, UBS announced a capital increase of no less than 13 billion Swiss francs.
In return, it actually found investors, albeit some of whom, until a short while ago, some would have racked their noses at: an opaque Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign wealth fund so secretive that one did not even know its name.
But that was just the first blow.
Things got worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new losses of billions. Marcel Ospel, Chairman of the Board of Directors, who in 2006 was still the second best paid member of the Board of Directors in Switzerland, resigned.
In October 2008, the disaster ensued: UBS was on the verge of collapse due to its bad investments in the financial crisis and had to be bailed out by the state.
The National Bank bought UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, and the Swiss Confederation gave six billion Swiss francs for a convertible bond, through which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because it noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to host such large banks.
After all, UBS's balance sheet total in 2007 was more than five times Switzerland's economic output (see chart).
"Once again, we couldn't save UBS," says Geiger, a banking analyst.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
Only a few months later, UBS capitulated in a tax dispute with America, agreeing to release the data of wealthy clients who may have evaded taxes with the help of the bank.
It also agreed to pay $780 million in restitution for unwarranted profits from those deals, along with a penalty.
In doing so, UBS more or less openly confessed to having assisted in tax evasion.
At the same time, it lost something that had always been its capital in the competition for rich customers: the aura of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the CEO and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Within a few months, the bank had lost credibility in both key areas of its business: investment banking due to false speculation and asset management due to tax evasion.
And just as things quietened down, just when it was thought that UBS would be able to do it again, here follows this unfortunate trader story: a single trader gambles away 1.7 billion euros before the bank notices that something is wrong.
And it is becoming apparent that risk management in investment banking is still not working.
"The Adoboli case has shown that risk control has changed too little," said Martin Janssen, an economist and finance professor at the University of Zurich's banking institute.
Even the CFO of a large German bank is certain: "The problem for UBS is that it does not have a grip on risk control."
Yet it was precisely the idea of prudence with which Swiss bankers had long ago embarked to become custodians of the world's great fortunes: not too great risks, but security for money - even if the world were to collapse beyond the Alpine republic.
The safes of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unshakeable reliability, just as Lindt and Sprüngli had become symbols of particularly fine chocolate.
UBS's Zurich headquarters fit the stereotype of the dignified Swiss private bank - it's just a bit bigger.
The location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Züricher Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly from the main station to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewellers such as Tiffany's can be found here between traditional Swiss shops such as Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank to the palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
You enter the UBS reception hall through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are covered in marble, in front of them are thick leather chairs, next to the bank logo a large sign indicating the "safe."
UBS knows what its customers are looking for: security.
However, both major Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, eventually supplanted this idea of a Swiss bank - or betrayed it, according to the head of a small Swiss private bank.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper because, like all Swiss bankers, he does business with the two big banks.
UBS has become far too big, he says - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also spread.
The Swiss would have nothing more to say there.
"And if they do, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
Indeed, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that transformed UBS, giving it first high profits, and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the catastrophe became visible.
"That Wednesday, the governing coalition of the small country of seven million decided on the largest bailout in its nation's history," the author Lukas Hässig writes in his book "The UBS Crash."
The politicians approved up to 68 billion Swiss francs, or around 45 billion euros, to rescue the big bank, which is facing bankruptcy.
How could this have happened?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged to form a formidable group.
The result was a bank that was already too big for little Switzerland at the time of the merger - and continued to grow.
It helped that the two different forerunners of UBS complemented each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalised bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers got cheap money to turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, Chief Executive Officer of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team," says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the highly intellectual, humble man who understands a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man who has worked his way up from banking to the very top."
But in the end Ospel relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a crucial mistake in the end: "He thought his models were reality," Geiger says.
'It's a tragic case. '
Tragic, perhaps.
What is clear is that exuberance came before the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly uttered the same slogan: "Get rid of Goldman Sachs."
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She topped the league tables, the league tables that documented the success of the banks of the time.
That's where UBS wanted to go, to the very top.
She had already succeeded in a few steps.
It was at the top of the foreign exchange and share market.
However, management consultants who were appointed highlighted a weakness: in the international interest rate business, in the banking language of fixed income, there was a huge gap with the largest banks.
UBS has loopholes in American mortgage products, he said.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost it its existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund set up before it invested in American subprime assets.
It became a huge machine, packaging and passing on securities on American mortgage loans - but also retaining risks.
Even when other banks were already looking to exit.
"Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there," says banking expert Geiger.
So great the euphoria, so deep the fall.
One manager after another had to go when the clean-up efforts turned out to be more difficult than expected.
Items at UBS have become an ejection point and remain shaky to this day.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He needs to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all the obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: stop investment banking, concentrate on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The Bank does not want to go quite that far (yet).
But investment banking is to shrink sharply, that much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new head of the bank, Sergio Ermotti, will present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was only meant to be a temporary solution when the bank unexpectedly parted ways with predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has prevailed: he is to lead the business of UBS on a permanent basis, the Zurich-based bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring the investment bank back to where it was in the mid-1990s.
He is cutting 3,500 jobs.
But that will not be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
How does she want to make money?
These are the questions Axel Weber must be asking himself right now.
Publicly, he has so far said only that he and his wife will first look for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
