Smart Crows Spread in Cities
In many places, seed crows are regarded as "problem birds": however, the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of cities, experts claim.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: Crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities residents complain about the dirt and noise of the animals.
A remedy for the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer possible to get out of the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in Leer, East Frisia.
There, experts from all over Germany discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of specially protected seed crows: Chemical use in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the felling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are under conservation.
There are large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs in Soest in Westphalia, in the northwest in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county made negative headlines.
Critics had described trapping the animals in bird traps and killing them with clubs as particularly brutal.
"Normal expulsion, degradation, is useless," stated the town and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer.
Spraying away nests with water or felling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals move away, large colonies split up and disperse in other places."
Grief is only conceivable as an exception at hospitals, nursing homes or schools.
'We have to live with them, we can't get them away. '
Without the surrounding area the problem in the cities cannot be solved, said mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable that a combination of mutilating the animals from sensitive living areas and attraction offers could be used to resettle them in other places.
On the other hand, psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens called for a completely different way of dealing with animals: "After all, we are best able to tolerate a pimple on the face with self-confidence."
Jürgens co-founded the Ascheberg Crow Trail in Schleswig-Holstein, where signs provide information about the lives of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project has already been accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of the birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and dexterity of the animals are legendary: Seed crows not only use aids to get a treat, but also make their own tools as aids.
Behavioural researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested how far the birds' intelligence reaches on four rooks.
In an experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to use stones to bring down a scaffold in order to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they purposefully recognized the size and shape of a stone in order to cause the platform to collapse.
In a second attempt, the smart crows then had to solve a trickier problem.
In a vertically positioned cylinder, the researchers placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
The birds could not reach their prey with the beak.
However, the researchers had placed pieces of wire in front of them.
From this, all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle out of the tube.
Three of the four Seed Crows even managed to do so straight away.
