Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many blokes posting their anti-immigration views online.
On Monday Breivik, who has confessed to being involved in a July rampage in Norway in which 77 people were killed, had his first public court hearing.
Though Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent much time in front of his computer before his attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networks.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it wasn't hard to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on digital populism in Europe by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook's stash of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with ads, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to take part in a survey asking about their education level, attitudes towards violence and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without having to leave their offices even once.
"It's a fairly new research method," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male, and resent immigration.
But, in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more sensible, democratic, and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a hot new tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends like "likes," text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom that has boosted the number of scientific papers bearing the site's name in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it lets you study people you don't normally reach on the street with your clipboard.
'If you used to try to interview people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them, 'he said.
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have allowed them in," Bartlett says.
'With Facebook, it's all gone - you go straight to them. '
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their binge drinking on Facebook were significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that peers, such as housing counselors, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you don't recognize it," Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, told The Washington Post.
'We found a way to identify vulnerable children who wouldn't have been found otherwise. '
