7 lessons from the interview with the late Steve Jobs, which was shown in a theater this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the technological genius as a great modern inventor.
But perhaps what Apple fans find most revealing in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted off this week ahead of special screenings in major markets, is how much this creative mind understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who worked diligently on diagrams - a man who believed that many CEOs suffer from "a disease of thinking that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there is an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of Professional Idiots," about the dawn of the personal computer. And he sat with Jobs for more than an hour, during which they had one of the rare in-depth conversations.
By then, it had been more than 10 years since Jobs had been forced out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company, NeXT, and looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley's interview was used in technical idiots, he says the interview's copies were missing on delivery.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview," which hits theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to loathe in-depth interviews, Jobs appears surprisingly zealous here in explaining his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
During the course of the interview, there are four long pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs's perfectionism comes to the fore, when he seems impatient to respond to Cringely's questions and nudges him to respond more quickly to themes or subplots of greater importance.
Taken before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, The Lost Interview somehow seems eerily prescient when Jobs assesses what he thinks other companies are doing right or wrong and presents his own vision of the future of the computer.
It's one thing to read posthumous tributes to Jobs's career, but to see Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the verge of greatness is something very different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could be and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he set off and did it.
A quick look at seven notable sequences from the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"Throughout the years in business, I always ask," Why do you do things? "And the answer you always get is," Oh, that's just how it's done. "
Nobody knows why he does what he does. Nobody in the business really thinks about things.
That's what I found.
Jobs is continuing his efforts to streamline Apple's accounting.
Baffled by the way costs were recorded - most often starting with "standard costs," which were calculated purely on guesswork, and then adjusted with "deviation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined to the smallest detail.
How the Pope was made a fool of:
Jobs talks about the "blue box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that could be used to sneak into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs's enthusiasm when he describes the blue box as an act of self-empowerment is infectious.
He describes how he and Wozniak would test the box by using a paid phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent stuff half a dozen times around the globe, and when you hollered into the phone, it came out a minute later in the phone next door," Jobs says, giggling.
"We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
We both, we didn't know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don't think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to recount a glorious prank that he and Wozniak almost pulled off when they called in the middle of the night via the Vatican Blue Box and wanted to talk to the Pope while imitating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself got on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called Bill Hewlett unprepared):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"It had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was the size of a suitcase, it had a small screen with a brown tube and I fell in love with it.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to that machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview Jobs talks about spontaneously inventing new products.
Early in his career, when he was installing some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the whole computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple he remembers the problems he had developing a computer mouse:
"I remember the arguments... They shouted at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later we had a mouse that we could build for $15, which was incredibly believable.
On big companies that are slowing down:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their shares.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so make a better copier or printer, so what?"
They have a monopoly on shares, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it's those people] who end up running the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly is being eradicated by people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times bigger if it had been Microsoft in the 1990s...
They took defeat from victory.
About innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop that great idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
You have to vote, certain things you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
At the end of the day, it comes down to taste, it comes down to trying to deal with the best stuff that people have created and then trying to bring those things together into what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who work there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who just happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for the computer industry, they would be doing fantastic things in other areas.
