How to unmask a lie
A glance at the current headlines shows how dubious and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is dealing with allegations of sexual harassment from several women, with both sides accusing each other of lying.
Penn State's leadership has been accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was overheard on an open microphone telling American President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself by circulating denials that were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who witnessed it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton created when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories of cheating at school and on college exams are common.
There have been instances where teachers have given their students the answers to the exam so that they would do well in their own performance tests.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
But many of these lies are false.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or "uncovering lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a parlor game, such as charades, in which the goal is to shout "Have you!," unmasking a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have undertaken far-reaching research projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They stutter, stammer, blush and fidget not always.
However, we must not conclude from this that these liars are difficult to detect and unmask.
A trained lie-detector can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the assertion, the subtle facial expressions, about question-setting and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the vast and ever-growing field of unmasking, and it is clear that unmasking an illusion is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us navigate our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or managing is one of our professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at judging other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively feel how others perceive them.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverts are more likely to lie than introverts, that men are more likely to tell "self-oriented" lies than women, whose lies are more "oriented" - usually to protect others "feelings - and that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly" fat lies ").
We also know that when one person is exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you tell if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of that person.
This is called "baselining," the starting position.
It provides a point of reference for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the vocal quality of their subjects.
They should know better when someone is normally kicking his foot all the time, so that they do not wrongly accuse him of kicking his foot during a meeting.
Then watch out for clusters of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Think of these clusters as alarm bells ringing, not proof of exposure.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story, perhaps point their feet toward the door, or lean toward the exit, change their position in a significant way, or show a "relaxation after the interview," that deep, relaxing exhalation, and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often wrongly signal that a job interview is over, only to look for that relaxation after the job interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slip-up is famous for using the past tense when he claimed his slain wife was still alive, sparking a national search for her.
Deceptive people can also use distancing language: "I did not have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or when repeating a tricky question in its entirety.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual, often sounding alarm bells.
There is no magic bullet to unmask lies, but you can learn skills to unmask them.
Thanks to these skills, everyone is less likely to fall victim to fraudsters, both in their private and professional lives.
