Climate adversity slowed the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez has been in power, unemployment and undeclared work have risen in Sinaloa, while foreign investment has declined and the economy has stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the instigator of change and raised high hopes for economic growth, is in power. However, due to the climatic adversity, there can be no talk of growth; on the contrary, the main economic indicators have deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of dollars in losses in agriculture, but also placed tight constraints on the growth of the state economy and caused an overall decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historic 31.16 percent decline in agricultural development, which slowed down other economic sectors.
According to a report on the effects of the frost issued by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which was completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially. Vegetable, maize and chickpea cultivation were particularly affected.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, with 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa out of work from January to March, representing 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18,969 more people than in the first quarter.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa this year is due to several factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences at the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing at the moment is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including liquidity losses in the market as a result of the cuts in funding by the legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, because it is not easy for those who illicitly accumulate dollars to let them work for themselves, invest in them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration halted
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased, partly because of immigration problems and partly because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here and look for work, which increases unemployment," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the Sinaloa labor market is even more serious when one considers the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 percent of the country's workers who work without paying into social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are compounded by low wages, the lowest in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Agency for Employment and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers as of September was 5352 pesos, much less than the national average of 7375 pesos.
Decline in FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and growing unemployment, 2011 will see the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last decade. According to the Secretaría de Economía, the FDI amounted to 630 597 dollars from January to June, a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to 5 143 312 dollars in the same period last year.
For its part, the Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) has recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.

In view of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in order to reactivate the economy, and the State Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but by November no positive effects of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be observed.

For business representatives, the first year of Mario López Valdés "reign revealed his inability to govern.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), argued that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa has been really poor this year, hard work is needed to recover the territory lost this year, and in 2012 we will have to make a double effort. Everyone's efforts, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic growth
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year hampered and slowed the country's economic development.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowing economy that is not moving sufficiently to generate an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services, so we will finish the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Confederation of Mexican Entrepreneurs) in Sinaloa, said that the state should be encouraged to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There is a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that directs the government's efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in a number of areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He emphasized that the current state power has made progress in the government.
"There are areas where it can be said that the government has acted more broadly, and what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
