The court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The conversion of analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Mexican Supreme Court (SCJN) rejected the constitutional challenges filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which requires the switch from analog to digital signals to be brought forward from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes needed to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers when he issued the decree with the details of the switchover to digital terrestrial television.
With this resolution, the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate was rejected, as it did not receive the qualified majority of eight votes required for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the project for the lawsuit, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, since the regulations concerning radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), so the decree would contradict the hierarchical principles and the legal reservations.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the decree. After the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the decree and ceased all activities to set up the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint lodged by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, which was also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the project in the sense that the state government should not regulate with general rules the measures that the public administration should take.
"Nor do I believe that doing so would affect the independence of the regulator." She also recalled that, for constitutional reasons, the planning of strategic policy areas, such as telecommunications, is the responsibility of the central government, which is in charge of state affairs.
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
Delaying the changeover, she said, was delaying the benefits of digitization, which was a decision in the public interest that was not only technical, "because it included economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she emphasized, "required the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic management by the state, they included a set of features that the Constitution placed in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already made the digital switchover through the government, even though they had highly specialized facilities.
It cannot be concluded that by issuing the contested decree, the government is interfering with the powers of Congress, because the laws passed by the legislature will be complied with, "she asserted.
The possibility of counting ballots individually in Michoacán is being considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the election for governor is just under 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6,074 not yet counted.
The possibility of a single count of ballots is a reality in this year's elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Program for the Preliminaries of the Electoral Results (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6,074 that have not yet been counted.
With this in mind, the President of the General Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last 9 November, the electoral office adopted a set of rules harmonizing local rules with state electoral reforms.
It is recalled that Michoacán did not adapt its political constitution, electoral law or electoral justice law to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they did not enter into force in this election round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Gazette within the time limits set for them, arguing that he did not object to them.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional challenge lodged by the local legislature, ruling that the State Ombudsman's vote on the constitutional reforms was "invalid and unlawful," as he did not have the right to "decide or veto" it.
María de los Ángeles Llanderal, in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes, said that, thanks to the adoption of the directives by the Consejo General del IEM, it is now possible for the local electoral authority to count all or part of the ballots.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted. The results in the minutes do not coincide; the minutes of the counting and calculation of votes are not available on the file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the election committee, or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, if there is a difference between the presumed winner and the runner-up, which is equal to or less than one percent, the total number of fully completed ballot papers may be counted, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an express request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
The vote count may also take place in its entirety if, after the ordinary calculation has been completed, it is determined that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an express request from a representative of the party whose candidate has come second. In this case, the electoral packages that have been subjected to a partial count would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just 0.16%, even though the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
