On Wednesday, formation of the new Italian government
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government designed to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government designed to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm the formation of a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, though it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of talks with the political parties to form a government.
"I would like to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," the former Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments indicate that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The framework is now well defined," he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, much less time than normal, while Italy is battling a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of its debt to intolerable levels.
The new government, led by former Commissioner Monti, must pass a tough austerity package demanded by euro leaders in order to regain confidence in Italy.
The rush pressure on Monti has been exacerbated by the volatile market, which has left Italian government bonds with a 10-year interest rate of 7%, the same level as when Greece and Ireland were forced to seek a European bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industry association Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government to the full."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency.
Monti's chances of success have been greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign on Saturday in the wake of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to produce good results," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is essential because, until now, many of its members have spoken out against the majority technocrat government that Monti is forming.
Support from Parliament
Monti's new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the likely unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to his efforts, or delaying reforms, could lead to another devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Federation of Foreign Banks is also pressing ahead, saying that Monti's failure would be a disaster.
Monti began his debates on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as with youth and women's organisations.
The session is due to conclude on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has set in motion an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief sigh of relief at the end of last week, when it was announced that Berlusconi would step down, uncertainty over the new prime minister's success has pushed the cost of Italian government bonds back to critical levels.
A bailout of Italy, with a national debt of €1.8 trillion, would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said his government would have to wait until the next elections, expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians would only give him time to implement the reforms rather than bring forward the elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist that it should be made up only of technicians, an indication of their concerns about the process imposed by financial market pressure.
Political sources point out that mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the involvement of political figures.
