Looking back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for more than 20 years. It's like a dream.
We continue to count on this blessing and think it's great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are passionate about making music.
We are lucky to be able to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of grunge?
It has always been an honour to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual for a movement to arise from a group of friends.
Every now and then a band emerges from a city, but it is unusual for five or ten groups to come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are happy to still be friends with all of them and we are honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a lot more time than a lot of bands survive.
First of all, I think we are all lucky to be alive, and we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up, giving everyone the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't be better off.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to tour too much because it is too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what it brought to life without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. We never cared about that anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some very good songs and in the beginning it was great.
For three years we were a band that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We're still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we will miss him.
The local band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band the most, so we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live, which will be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who were you influenced by as a bass player?

Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge alive, even though it's no longer a fad?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they're still important today, I think that's great because it's worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever before.
In the beginning her music was darker, now it is more positive.
Why?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit frivolous, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although there is something positive about them.
They both brought tears to my eyes when I heard Ed play them. They are very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example when you lose a family member or a friend - it affects your art and your music and these two songs embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
