Fujimori returned to hospital for medical checks
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the loss of muscle in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his rule (1990-2000), has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congressman and his personal physician, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas in Peru to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned on humanitarian grounds. Nevertheless, he did not wish to do so because he considers him innocent.
He has undergone four surgeries for tongue cancer and lost 18 kilos, as well as other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been held in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which operated clandestinely during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and businessmen will begin their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday, which the Uruguayan president says will be the culmination of his packed schedule of meetings with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "lends itself to the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica sought Calderón's support over the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that still operate as tax havens, a declaration rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request from its ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and developed economies, since November. Since January this year, an agreement has been in place with the South American country on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the finalization of tax information exchange agreements in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not adopted all international standards for tax cooperation.
On a commercial level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to an increasing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The mustachioed plumber enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
For 25 years, Super Mario has fought tirelessly to rescue Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never in three dimensions: in Super Mario 3D Land, he fights for the girl's love in stereo technology.
The game, which hits store counters around the world this month, has been tailored from the start to the characteristics of the Nintende 3DS portable console, which can play in three dimensions without the need for special glasses.
"Mario is the figure who has to explain how stereoscopy works without glasses," said Omar Álvarez, who is in charge of the Nintendo press in Spain, at the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez explained that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first video game from Nintendo that has been developed for this console from the beginning," because until now successful games like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman stressed that although it is three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows for fast, fluid play.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: the first part is "easy" to capture the less savvy users.
After that, the experts can take a "second turn" on the different levels of the game, which are getting more and more difficult.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. However, in order to overcome the obstacles without falling victim to the "optical effects," it is always necessary to play in three dimensions.
Super Mario's foray into the three-dimensional world also means the character's return to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winks at the fans of the saga and repeats the recipe for success of recent editions: the mustachioed plumber must overcome perilous platforms to free Princess Peach.
However, the player comes across novelties in the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom guarantees Portillo's extradition to the United States
The President of Guatemala, Álvaro Colom, announced this Tuesday that he would authorize the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo to face charges in the United States of conspiring to launder USD 70 million.
That is how the trial ends on the US request for Portillo's extradition so that he can be tried there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the government, taking into account that a decision-making court had already ordered the extradition.
He stressed that during his government he had not interfered in court decisions and had granted all extradition requests of which he had been informed.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's action is an act of government that takes place when all judicial and constitutional instances for the sentencing of the former President of the State (2000-2004) have been exhausted.
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemale has been clarified and his human rights guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of embezzling 120 million quetzales in the Ministry of Defense during his reign, a trial that preceded extradition, but the minister objected and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organisation was set up to prevent the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the Trinijove social assistance organisation have yielded important results: in this quarter of a century, 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion have been helped to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
Yesterday, on the occasion of the anniversary, more than 300 people attended an event in the former Fabra i Coats factory premises to take stock of the situation.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the district of Trinitat Vella with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, unemployed, with drug problems, who were at risk of marginalization.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by many persons in charge of institutions and institutions that have collaborated with the Association in these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different persuasions at election time proved the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the celebrations were attended by the former Socialist Minister of Education, Ernest Maragall, and the former mayor and current left-green councillor Ricard Goma.
The Great Hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, Josep Lluís Cleries, and Jaume Lanaspa, Director General of the Social Work Department of La Caixa Savings Bank.
Mas emphasized that Trinijove was created in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but added that the work done so far "is a good foundation."
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is a model who knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it is doing," he said.
Squatted house where giant parties were held has been evacuated
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Balmes Street (Barcelona).
The 12 squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without having resisted.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of House 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they had illegally occupied yesterday lunchtime, where they had organised huge parties that had driven the neighbourhood to despair, and the eviction was ordered by a judge without police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was changed to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," the property manager confirmed.
The squatters, who had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest were inhabited - took all the electrical equipment and part of the water supply with them, painted the walls and left all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were held on the three lower floors, lasting up to two days, driving the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had fallen by 80% since the squatting began.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters were making unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while in the discotheque they cost 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the leisure centre had been reported by the neighbours for disturbing the peace, while, according to her, the noise did not come from the visitors to the disco, but from the squatters and, in particular, from the guests of the parties that were organised there, which, according to the disgruntled neighbours, have been getting longer and longer in recent weeks.
The person in charge of the nightclub explained that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building that she would not have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (Metropolitan Police) also confirmed that it had received more complaints from neighbours in recent weeks.
The leader of the PP (Partido Popular - Popular Party) in the Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, demanded last week that the building be evacuated immediately and that the problems of civic coexistence and the downfall of the neighbourhood be dealt with.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in recent months the squatters had penetrated all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments. In some cases, there had even been thefts.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and crack down on the anti-social acts in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris neighbourhood was evacuated by Catalan police.
At 3: 30 p.m., the police approached 35 Montral Street after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people trying to enter the building.
The four were arrested immediately.
Park or mountain?
Apart from the disputes over fees, the architects agree to the tender.
The municipal tender for the 16 gates reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its diatribe on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It has even been compared in numbers to New York's Central Park.
With the sinking of the CMB in 1987, the park became in the eyes of many the upper limit of Barcelona, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not extend in a north-south direction, but up (mountains) and down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park plays with this idea.
The model was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the yoga bear.
That was the situation when, in September, the city issued a huge call for tenders, consisting of 16 competitions, for additional access gates to Collserola.
There is no doubt that a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either that or someone intends to put gates up in the countryside.
The question arises: Collserola, park or mountain?
The call for tenders is the topic on the lips of all Barcelona architects, not only from an organisational point of view, but also with a view to reflecting on the city.
It is almost a recurrent theme that two members of this long-established caste, who meet in an elevator, can fall back on.
And it is this fact that provides the material for one of the rare similarities between what three Barcelona architects think about it and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán, after the attack on the coast, "it is necessary" to talk about the "front in the mountains," as far as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, about the green apples, has not been carried out.
"One should start from the principle that Barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Partly because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex, "declares the architect, for whom the title" Gates of Collserola "entails a" lexical trap ": it must not be imagined" as an entrance to a park, but as a delimitation of areas in which action is needed. "
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban planning experience, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" that carries "some dangers."
Dangers arising from the "uncertainty that the design of a public space entails nowadays" after the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the forum area.
The first fear is to restrict oneself to what may be cultivated.
"Limiting something always means determining the next step," i.e. exceeding it.
"New urban planning instruments need to be considered, because the current ones [referring to the General Metropolitano Plan (PGM)] can lead to a real catastrophe."
Modol, who is closer to the question, says simply that the side of Collserola that goes in the direction of Vallesana "can be understood as a park that does not go in the direction of Barcelona," for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronat de Collserola that "should not fall on deaf ears," although he is grateful to the Municipality for giving his committee the opportunity to participate in this project "from the very beginning."
He also notes that the proximity of the mountains to the city is the guideline that allows architects to take part in the debate, although he expresses "doubts" about whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams that have been set up ("just the thing," he says) "We architects should be just a tool."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, as the terms of the tender lack a global view of Collserola: "There were 16 cross-section competitions," he says, "on the mountain-sea axis. But there is no longitudinal perspective that looks at the area as a whole."
That, at least in his case, has led to him taking part in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt is equipped along its entire length in such a way that a smooth transition between the city and green areas is created.
Casino forgives Jonás Larrazábal, who is released
After 72 days of silence, the commissioner of Casino Red released the brother of the mayor of Monterrey from the case against him for alleged extortion.
After 72 days of imprisonment, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal is released after the commissioner of Casino Red forgives him in the Second Criminal Court of the District, which is conducting the extortion case against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on Casino Royale, Sergio Gil García, the owner of Casino Red, published a series of photos and videos showing Manuel Jonás allegedly forcing him to pay a sum of money to get the municipality to authorise the clandestine operation of the betting house.
Following the lawsuit, the Procuratorate opened criminal proceedings against the brother of the panicked mayor, who was arrested for 30 days on September 2nd.
After four hours with the official of the Ministerio Público 3 en Delitos Patrimoniales, he was taken to Casa de Arraigo 1 in the Barrio Antiguo of the capital.
He remained there 49 days after a second arrest warrant was issued, after the official of the Ministerio Público rejected the charges of bribery and organized crime.
On 19 October, he was transferred to the Cadereyta Detention Centre for allegedly bribing the owners of Casino Red with one and a half million pesos. However, he only spent a few hours on the medium security wing because of death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to participate in the trial as an inmate of the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On 25 October, the secretary of the Second Criminal Court of the District, Jorge Yánez, issued a warrant for his arrest, stating that, after almost two months of investigation, there was sufficient evidence to convict Jonás of paying 1.5 million pesos to the betting house's representatives in exchange for opening it.
This Monday, the commissioner of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, asked Judge José Luis Pecina, the mayor's brother, to release him in the next few hours.
During the court hearing, Ramiro Arias, the official of the Ministerio Público assigned to the court, asked García Gómez whether he had repaired the damage and which one of the owners of the betting house had forgiven him, but the lawyer withheld the name.
In accordance with Case 197 / 2011, Jonás Larrazábal is acquitted and no appeal can be lodged against the trial and no compensation is sought.
Larrazabal Breton was released immediately following a hearing with the betting house's procurator fiscal at around 3.50pm.
The court secretary, Jorge Yánez, went to the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonás that he had been acquitted and that his case would be closed.
He also informed him of the judge's order for his immediate release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that killed government secretary Francisco Blake and seven other people.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat of Communications and Transportation in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation into the accident, in which the Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people died, indicate that the helicopter with all its intact structure crashed directly onto the ground, without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller blades came into contact with trees at a height of 25 metres, with the helicopter losing its fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had made several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it met all the requirements for transporting personnel.
He also said no helicopter parts were found in the area where the plane came down.
"No aircraft parts were found in other places during the search, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it fulfilled all requirements for transporting passengers.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
At the moment, the priority is to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but it could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, General Manager of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Emergency Services in Mexico), confirmed that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial had been flying at cruising speed on impact and that the plane had fallen onto a soft slope.
'This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact, 'he said.
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at take-off. During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico City and Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds were gathering.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the crew chose a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Impact site:
The co-ordinates of the impact and the last radar recording of the helicopter match. Possibly, there was neither a loss of control over the aircraft nor a deviation from the flight path before the impact.
Scattering the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter had crashed from both a straight and a lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered remains of the aircraft suggests that the helicopter, with its intact structure, had hit the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the plane do not indicate fire or explosion at the scene of the accident.
The latest results of the investigation indicate several soil contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter is likely to have broken up.
Some information suggests the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a painstaking search in an area that went beyond the cordoned-off area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had crashed to the ground.
MSS Announces a Research Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
She is leading a research project to find the obesity gene in children and adolescents, which is being supported by specialists at the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (IMSS) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for childhood and adolescent obesity, entitled "Genetics of childhood and adolescent obesity," aimed at identifying the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8 am.
He stressed that the investigation began at the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of Mexico) and will continue since 8 October at the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of Mexico).
Once the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will be continued at the Independencia sports field (in the south of the capital district) and completed at the Morelos sports field (in the north of the capital district).
He said the aim of the study was to understand the factors and role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for prevention of chronic degenerative diseases in Mexican children and adolescents.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he said that the aim was for three thousand children and adolescents between the ages of six and 14 to complete nutrition questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family history of illness in order to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He also explained that on the Saturdays mentioned above, the subjects were measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (an attempt to identify genes related to childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López said the study was carried out in response to health workers' concerns about alarming weight gain among young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 per cent and that of girls with obesity by 47 per cent. Obesity also increased dramatically," emphasised the specialist from the IMSS.
He said the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the Mexican population was different from that of other peoples.
He stated that, on average, a Mexican is 65 percent Indian-American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
More generally, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) we consume, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher said the direct benefit for the study participants would be a comprehensive study of the children to determine whether they were overweight or obese.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the early stages.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to parents in writing by doctors, who would explain all measurement results to parents and propose lifestyle changes that are appropriate to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that are responsible for overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of daily exercise, spending most of the day in front of the TV, and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, is developing asphalt modified with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations.
If the signs emanating from the road surface were observed, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes when the rainy season breaks out in the Metropolitan Zone of Mexico Valley, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning that if the asphalt surface is properly laid and maintained, the number of potholes will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Potholes from a technical point of view," which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the performance of the road surface and thus prevent the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other a low one - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic viscous elastic behaviour.
Viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180 ° C, at 120 ° C it is very viscous and at 50 ° C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," explained the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the majority of the streets of Mexico City have a flexible pavement made up of six layers of material, the last three of which contain asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer enables a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be distributed even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid, the so-called base layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand that has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, it requires a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
In addition to receiving and distributing the most forces from this road surface, the base layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material of which it is composed needs to be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to take into account, especially water, "he said," because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes damp, water penetrates the layer and is difficult to escape, causing softening of all layers of the road surface and consequently the occurrence of potholes.
"When a pothole occurs," he said, "the top layer is removed first, and the wear layer is affected only afterwards, but the damage is not immediate; it is a process that should be maintained by appropriate maintenance programs at the first signs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is respected in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and which could be used to repair potholes easily and without using high temperatures.
