Such was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Cali ophoscopist went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last 4 November, a ophoscopist from the Investigative Unit of the Prosecutor's Office (CTI) of Cali arrived as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): "Alfonso Cano" by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven ophoscopists in the department of the CTI, this week Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, had on-call duty.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities in Chocó, where he often had to go into the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses he specialised in ophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
He flew by helicopter from Palmira to Cauca on Friday night.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that there was a suspicion that one could be that of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he had to take the ten-finger print of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name) with him.
However, when he reached the site of the corpse with the examiner, he was unable to identify it because of his physical appearance, which did not resemble the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a trowel and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse to those on the imprint sheet.
He was right: It was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of informing the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was in fact the head of the FARC.
Searching for clues
For a dactyloscope from the Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given by the president Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference about the operation against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no margin for error that can be a key factor in solving a crime.
Lophoscopists do not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murders and robberies and confirm the identity of the persons arrested.
At the time of their arrest, many offenders present false identification documents or they do not have one.
We take their fingerprints and search the database.
The researcher told us that in case of a theft he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had propped himself up with his hand right there when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for taking fingerprints, but in this case we were able to take the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also be used to exonerate or charge murder suspects.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
The investigation suggested that a family member could be a suspect, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that the murderer is involved, it is nevertheless linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints are taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a trowel or ribbon is used to take them with you.
Afterwards the prints are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the CTI expert.
He said that not everything is as it is portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a comparison.
