Medical care or not: 77% of Canadians do not have access to painkillers, according to experts appointed by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the majority of Canadians wanting to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Looking at the country as a whole, Quebec has the highest rate of hospitalized deaths, at 86%.
On the thorny issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it does not wish to make any changes to the penal code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also inspected all those countries whose approach has legalised or decriminalised euthanasia and assisted suicide, there is no evidence that such decriminalisation would lead to abuses in its application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide by incompetent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, there are many more cases of such transgressions in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalised, as Jocelyn Downie, a co-signatory of the report, confirmed in a teleconference yesterday.
'Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it's clearly illegal. '
"Accompanied suicide is also practised in Canada, although clearly illegal here," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians support euthanasia
Let us remember that, according to an Angus Reid survey carried out in 2010, 85% of Canadians were already in favour of euthanasia, believing that it would allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering.
And 66% believe that legalising euthanasia does not send the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled are of less value.
With regard to those who have already committed assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
The report's authors say the situation is less clear when it comes to maintaining or stopping treatment for patients.
In the same way, they suggest in their list of recommendations that it should be stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of funds for which there had been a valid refusal should not be regarded as criminal.
The panel also calls for health professionals to be trained to respect end-of-life termination without fear of prosecution.
The panel said that governments, health care institutions, and physicians worked together on pain-relieving treatment to provide the best pain-relievers, even beyond cancer cases.
Lastly, with regard to pain relief or life-ending measures, which are already widely used in Canadian health care institutions, the panel calls for them at least to be considered, since these, like euthanasia, were not intended to reduce physical pain and related to the same procedures.
Reservations of other experts
Some health law experts have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the expert report by the Royal Society of Canada.
RA Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the stance of the experts who signed the report as "extreme," among other things, as it set no limits to euthanasia practice for the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation in which anyone who is tired of life and over 18 years of age can ask another person to assist him in his suicide," said RA Deschamps, who read a summary of the report yesterday.
RA Deschamps also stresses that the authors of the report seem to place individual responsibility above all other values involved in the social fabric of society.
But now, he says, there are "guidelines and obligations in a society."
Margaret Somerville, a health law specialist, also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's conclusions, which she called a "pro-euthanasia manifesto."
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, questions in particular the reports on the absence of abuses in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalised, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
