Russian Scientist Helps Iran's Nuclear Program
A Russian scientist, Vyacheslav Danilenko, has helped Iran develop a nuclear-capable warhead, an American NGO specialising in nuclear risks confirmed on Monday.
The ISIS Institute for Science and International Security based its findings on the recent report of the International Atomic Safety Agency (AIEA) and other documents issued by the agency to identify the scientist.
The AIEA said last week it had expressed "serious concern" about a "possible military dimension" to Iran's nuclear programme.
According to a detailed study of the AIEA documents by ISIS, Danilenko, born in 1934, had apparently worked for more than three decades in a Soviet military nuclear center in Chelyabinsk (Urals) since the beginning of the 1960s and was involved in the production of synthetic diamonds produced by explosions.
In 1989 or 1991, he is said to have left the centre to set up a company in Kiev that produces "nano-diamonds."
The economic difficulties of his company led him to contact the Iranian Embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
Prior to his return to Russia, he was said to have worked on an Iranian programme from 1996 to 2002.
In its most recent report, the AIEA noted "strong indications that Iran's development of" a nuclear explosive system "had been supported by the work of a foreign expert who was not only extremely knowledgeable in this technology, but also, as one official told the agency, had worked indispensably on this technology throughout his professional career directly on the military nuclear energy program of his country of origin."
Anti-Islamic crimes and offences have increased by 50%
Crime and offenses against Muslims increased by 50% from 2009 to 2010, while other racially or religiously motivated violent crimes either declined slightly or increased only slightly over the same period, according to FBI statistics released Monday.
