Austria
Inscription of a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution
The government of the large Social Democratic / Christian Democratic coalition in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include a "golden rule" in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also to avoid a possible downgrade by rating agencies in Austria's top credit rating (AAA).
It was the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the end of the Council of Ministers, despite the fact that Austria's public debt is 74.6%, well above the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the level of debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency had not suddenly fallen from AAA to AA +, we would have had to pay an additional three billion euros in interest every year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian Democrat Foreign Minister.
Austria is also complying with a request made at the Brussels summit of eurozone member states on 26 October: at that time, the heads of state and government had demanded that the reduction of public deficits be included in the constitution by the end of 2012, as well as a return to the equilibrium of public accounts, or through the adoption of an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian Government in this regard is similar to the "German model," since Germany was the first European country to introduce such a "rule" in the Constitution.
Until 2017, the structural budget deficit should decrease by 0.75% of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) each year; from 2017, the structural budget deficit of the state should not exceed 0.35% of GDP, whereas regional states and municipalities should have balanced budgets.
The objective is to eradicate budgetary debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Agreement within the 2020 / 21 horizon.
