Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogma
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, it is certainly energy policy.
Availability and cost of electricity have a direct impact on purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to use an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by the year 2050, if an enormous proportion of the world's population is not to be deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity consistently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
As a result, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is subjecting its decision to the need to find a replacement source that can be substituted, or in Switzerland, which is only planning to build the latest generation of nuclear power stations.
The United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, decided after Fukushima to add another unit to its park by restarting the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which focuses on renewable energy sources, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, particularly on Russia, due to increased reliance on imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal-fired power stations.
All these adverse effects will begin to be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark is cause for reflection.
Denmark, on the one hand, is the European leader in wind energy, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, and, on the other, it is one of the largest users of coal and gas, alternating with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are both 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the price of energy in the globalised economy is a key factor in competitiveness and a source of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage thanks to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the re-industrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price the vast majority of French people are no more willing to pay than they are to resist the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125, 00 direct and 410, 000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a plethora of specialised small and medium-sized enterprises to international markets, making them the creators of countless jobs.
If France were to decide to phase out nuclear power, a large proportion of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual export of capital goods and nuclear energy of EUR 6 billion would shrink more and more.
What electrician would commission an EPR designed to operate for sixty years if the demise of its producer was inevitable?
In order to solve the energy equation, it must be acknowledged that there is no miracle cure for the generation of electricity, any more than there is a devil's work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks on existing plants, such as the Flamanville plant.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves for their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the idea of security.
In the space of 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
Only one, at Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, with no human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the tragedy was brought about by reactor construction and infinite human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn its lessons from this accident, as it did after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach, as well as cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR represents a blueprint that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a halt to construction at Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competitors of Areva and EDF, giving them the green light to usurp the leading position in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is unavoidable and legitimate to seek the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvres to dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
Nicolas Sarkozy's immigration policy has been criticised from many angles - overburdening the police, judiciary and administrative bodies because of a policy of subordination to numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights," as France had called itself.
Recently, the harassment of foreign students by the authorities had dominated the newsreels, with the Minister of the Interior casually proclaiming (see Libération of 23 May) that France "does not need talents, bricklayers or waiters from abroad."
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is, in fact, a broad consensus between right and left on this issue.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country," and on the left by Michel Rocard, who said in 1990 that France "cannot absorb all the poverty of the world."
The only difference is the degree of generosity
Fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both right and left in 2005.
Both camps saw immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande limits himself to banalities that suggest that we can solve our "migration problems."
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an electoral impact, but it is economically costly.
As the economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists about the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages, and jobs in the countries of immigration.
Restricting immigration would undermine growth and damage the labour market.
Fears about migrants "influence are based on the notion that they threaten to substitute domestic workers, especially the low-skilled, by putting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than domestic wage-earners, as they focus on occupations in sectors that are underutilized in terms of jobs.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic wage laborers, the more skilled among the immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, so this complementarity between natives and migrants has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market.
Giovanni Peri calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants would result in a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this ignores the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring is conducive to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay, and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also make a net contribution to social security systems, averaging around 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person who emigrates to Germany at the age of 30 brings a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget on average over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy, when he took office, wished to make up for the missing intersections "with his teeth."
But these teeth, designed to deter immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, now it is up to us to think European democracy through
Democracy is a precious commodity; it is also a sensitive commodity.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after their invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, endured the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonel in Greece for the whole of the 20th century.
Some might have thought that it was enough to exercise the right to vote, and to do so in the most direct way possible, to see democracy triumph over its enemies once and for all.
It has been known since Napoleon "the little one" that it was a feature of the state of mind.
Universal suffrage, which is a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and may just as well become an "instrument of oppression," as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organisation, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social community spirit, justice.
The crisis in Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also, and first and foremost, a political and democratic crisis.
The change of heart of the Greek True / False referendum would have been doubly illuminating in this respect: on the one hand, the need for a vigorous return of politics, but on the other hand also the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered outdated.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted, and Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer heading in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by pushing for the success of the national referendum, which was organised according to necessities and in the wrong order.
A free pass for the European autocrat or a blindfolded leap into the void of nationalist retreat: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want a chopping block, but a collective task, fully justified, clear and steady, an election and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - we do not know, by the way, where the list ends - because there is only one crisis, and that is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bowing to the dictates of the markets and credit rating agencies, suffering from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
There is concern about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - and it is the whole of Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and thus each and every one of its member nations.
The urgency is to put popular sovereignty back in charge of the European project.
For it is up to the whole whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debt, free themselves from the markets and pave the way for a future through investment.
The exit from the crisis requires decisions at European level, which cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, without certainly leading us to ruin.
After a long period of fighting against this proposal by Jacques Delors and the Socialists, everyone is now urging European economic leaders to do so.
Agreed.
But to imagine this without political integration and stronger democracy - as the citizens want - would be another folly and another impasse.
We must embark on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
In order to create a republic in France, it was necessary to "create" republicans.
The revolution of interests alone could not suffice here.
This teaching remains valid.
We need to build a more integrated Europe economically.
This can only be achieved by creating a more democratic Europe politically, a truly European popular sovereignty.
We need Europeans in order to build Europe.
