The world trade fair for smart cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment is contactless technology, which enables payments to be made on public transport or to pay for purchases simply by holding the card to a reader.
Compared to 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless smart cards should be sold worldwide this year!
Its market share is expected to grow even further in 2012 (580 million units expected), representing over 10% of the global smart card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground on contactless payments, having long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region.
Some 26 million Visa cards already have this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
But the supermarkets are running out of steam.
As a result, Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCards this year.
In order to move to faster speeds, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
"Two major French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically distributing contactless chip cards to their customers in the future," announces Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only the first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A negligible percentage of devices have been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology required to carry out these transactions.
'They've fallen behind. '
'But at least they should be on a real upward trajectory next year, 'he said.
"We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the initiative.
Yesterday, Crédit Agricole announced the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale also said yesterday that it was preparing to launch an offer that would allow its customers to pay by contactless mobile phone.
Terrorist front goes from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about relations between al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long suspected links between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram appear to be confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel himself confirmed that Algiers had now "gained certainty."
"The way in which both organisations operate and the relationship between the intelligence services indicate clear cooperation," he said, without going into further detail.
Paris seems to be making a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January has brought to light a number of issues, he said.
The following day, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory, who were kidnapped by Aqmi supporters in a restaurant in Niamey, were allegedly killed at the same time as several of their captors in an operation carried out by the French special forces.
French and Nigerian investigators say they have found several phone chips belonging to the terrorists in the rubble at the scene.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of the telephone calls made leads to several interlocutors stationed in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), the investigators are particularly interested in the numbers of two interlocutors: one number leads to a Nigerian who had spent a long time in Maiduguri, a town in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram; the other leads to a man considered to be close to the Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but there is no doubt that clearer evidence is needed before we can talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Harem."
'But it's conceivable. '
"It has been known for years that the sect receives financial and intellectual support from outside and that it is increasingly active," said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "support services" have become increasingly evident, as have the speeches and operations of Boko Harem, which now point to the use of suicide bombers and increasingly sophisticated explosives bearing the same hallmarks as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since put pressure on Abuja to take account of the problems caused by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have, in fact, for a long time regarded the group as a community of Illuminati to whom special attention does not need to be paid.
Rapid success
Boko Haram, founded in 2002 in Maiduguri near a mosque, a school, and the fundamentalist Iman Mohammed Yusuf - which in Haoussa means "Western education is a disgrace" - is pursuing the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this impoverished region, the merger is experiencing rapid success.
It is politicizing itself and claiming strict adherence to Sharia law, while its affiliated activists are engaged in the fight against the godless central government.
Activists have targeted churches, bars and government offices.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants have been particularly active in stepping up attacks on police stations.
The reaction from Abuja, however, is, as usual, indifferentiated.
The army surrounds the city and 800 people are killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, who was taken prisoner, is killed in prison.
As a result, the sect is becoming increasingly radical, abandoning its strongholds in the north.
Last Christmas, it claimed responsibility for one attack in Jos, which claimed 80 lives, and another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram was blamed for a suicide bombing at its secure police headquarters in Abuja - the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes a prime international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which is to run from Mauritania to Nigeria and Somalia, has since alarmed all security experts.
While the Aqmi has occupied Mali and Niger, the Somalis of al-Shabaab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears to be a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting with President Goodluck Jonathan in Nigeria, Alain Juppé warned of Boko Haram and said he was ready to "share all the information."
The world of the Republican presidential candidates
Mitt Romney, Herman Cain and Rick Perry are vying for the White House on China, Iraq and aid to Israel.
Can a crisis-stricken America lead a complex world with simple, not to say simple, ideas?
Listening to the Republican presidential candidates, voters could almost get that impression.
For the past few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and their comrades-in-arms have been repeating their thunderous statements, as well as their statements on foreign policy, traditional Republican focal points.
There are slogans - often unsubstantiated - about China, Iran, and aid to Israel.
Mitt Romney, the frontrunner for the "Grand Old Party" nomination, threatened to take the Chinese to the WTO and accuse them of "currency manipulation," a leading issue in an America deeply irritated by the exodus of entire industries to Asia.
Stupid if this is to imply launching a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, a former ambassador to China under Obama and the only candidate who seems to have a mature vision of foreign policy, has almost cut off his air with emotion.
He had called for a tangible but constructive exchange of views with Beijing (also Obama's current stance).
But Huntsman has not been heard, as he has stagnated in the polls.
Reagan's likeness
Romney had also vowed military strikes on Iran if sanctions aimed at halting its nuclear program fail.
"If elected, I will stop Iran," he had said.
'If Obama gets re-elected, they'll get the bomb. '
He has also promised Israel increased military aid and accused Obama of failing to fulfill obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second-highest-placed candidate, for his part, is showing a shameful lack of judgment.
He recently called for countering China's military threat because Beijing is "trying to develop a nuclear power" - seemingly ignoring the fact that China has had military nuclear weapons since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and calls for military strikes against Iran, has said he is ready to deploy the American army in Mexico to fight drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, prohibited by Obama in 2009, was also endorsed by Cain, Perry and the candidate Michele Bachmann.
It's a far cry from John McCain, the 2008 Republican nominee, a foreign policy heavyweight.
The current presidential contenders counter that Reagan also had simple ideas and, despite all that, won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and had to pour water into his wine when it came to the subject of anti-terror.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, the premature withdrawal of his "boys" from Iraq, his indecision in Libya, which also earned him a reputation for weakness.
This hostility, however, is not quite so casual.
People are more likely to appreciate the positive national security record under Obama, which eliminated Bin Laden.
Since Iraq, it has been wary of military interventions that lead to paralysis.
And Obama surprises more appropriately by arguing that America needs to be rebuilt economically to revive its leadership.
Nord Stream, New Gateway to Russian Gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to deliver gas to the equivalent of 30 million homes.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendour and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline linking Russia and Germany directly below sea level on the Baltic Sea coast last Tuesday, accompanied by an orchestra and a gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon, and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte symbolically turned the steering wheel of the valve that carries Russian gas to the Western European grid.
The new gas pipeline is intended to deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first 1,224 km pipeline linking the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, allowing a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - equivalent to France's total consumption - is scheduled for completion by the end of 2012.
And one already hints at the possibility of building a third line on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely and timely completion of this enormous structure is a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any overland route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine).
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: they are now finding it harder to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, the most engaged in the debate, has not shied away from comparing the Nord Stream pipeline to a "new German-Soviet pact" linked to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of debilitating European energy, as the project has opened up a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has managed to push through its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries that consume heavily and run out of gas.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the degree to which the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom managers, many of whom are present in Lubmin, when it comes to gas pipelines.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technology.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel with a concrete sheath to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at a depth of about 200 m.
During their construction, minefields dating back to the Second World War had to be avoided.
"As a precaution, hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipe is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything along its entire length: neither valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was envisaged off the coast of Sweden, but those responsible for the project refrained from doing so, as the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state-owned company settle permanently on their shores.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller specified.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers, as the welds were estimated to have a leak resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled from a seagoing vessel for external observation purposes and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures one metre in diameter, is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the pipe at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device delivers the most accurate information on possible metal deformations upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The German companies E. ON and BASF (15.5% each) are also affiliated here, as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have formed a consortium called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to that company on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the quantity of gas actually transported," Jens Müller specified.
30% of the financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs for both pipelines should amount to EUR 7.4 billion.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are confident that they will recoup their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-forested coastline near Lubmin.
The 4.5 metre high valves form the gas exit gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is transmitted to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic metres of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created by an Italian company some fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair for adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognisable, with its black, rectangular cover, its elastic band, its eggshell-colored pages that have aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as it is known today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which has its headquarters in Milan, decided at that time to bring a distinguished design notebook on the market.
Maria Sebregondi, the company's technical advisor at the time, is in charge of the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called mole skin, which refers to a cotton lacquer used, for example, to cover upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is a far cry from the usual production in the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyer, as the notebook excites businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now employs more than 100 people and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centres and knows how to assert its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of the times and its new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exposition called "Detour," in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard print cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Benefiting from its success and this cultural zeitgeist, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diaries, fountain pens, computer cases... The brand offers the full range of articles.
A success that brings jealousy to the plan: In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, which is now Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of the company Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate for disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today marks the start of the 15th Work Week for the Disabled.
Despite a purposeful public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% against 9% of the total population.
Discouraging?
"No," emphasises Éric Blanchet, director-general of the Adapt association, which organises "Work Week for the Disabled." "
"The progress made over fifteen years is considerable."
'At the time, the unemployment rate wasn't double, it was three times that. '
'Nevertheless, there's still an enormous amount of work to be done. '
It must be said, however, that many obstacles remain for the disabled unemployed before they get a job.
It is more common among the elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them do not have A-levels and there are only 10,000 disabled among the 2.3 million students with higher education qualifications.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled compared with 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to get back into work and that "lie at the heart of the problem," says Christian Grapin, chief executive of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
What remains is the unspoken, the attitudes of mind, which are certainly evolving, but slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the magazine La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about the disabled," which was "over-represented" by "persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually inferior."
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to reach the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, which was enshrined in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, which date back to 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organisation charged with collecting contributions from companies that flout the law.
The proof is that between 2007 and 2011, the number of "fee-paying" establishments decreased, as did the amount paid, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased premiums, put a lot of pressure on companies," said Pierre Blanc. "
"But this improvement also reflects a real realization, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments with between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while companies with between 100 and 199 employees employ 82%.
Hazard: 'What a lucky'
Even before they faced the "Blue Tuesday evenings" (8: 45 p.m.), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens had not concealed the pleasure that the friendly game brought them.
It would be too far-fetched to say that there was collusion between them, but the picture speaks symbolically.
Sitting side by side in the stands at the Stade de France, George Leekens and Eden Hazard could well have made peace.
Five months on from the spirited gesture of his attacking player against Turkey, the Belgium national coach has won nothing but praise for his side.
'I'm very pleased with Eden, his progress and the fact that he's Belgian. '
"I want to look ahead," the Liller native assures.
As for the contrast between his portrayal of club and national team, "It's a unit that justifies everything."
'I'm in Lille all year round, which is not the case in Belgium. '
"It's time for me to start."
Hazard will arrive in Saint-Denis ahead of Friday night's match against Romania in order to 'finally shine'.
However, without neglecting the note of "pleasure."
He has been with the French national team since the age of seven and led their victorious campaigns between 1998 and 2000.
"I have always been supported," he said.
Inevitably, this contributes to further enhancing the "unique" character of this encounter.
"Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) will be there," he said.
'We've just run into each other. '
"To be able to play against them is great luck!"
Leekens, for his part, sounded "proud."
"The pride of hosting a gala match."
"Pride" also to confirm - in its capacity as "neighbour" - that France "has once again become a team at a very high level," little more than a year after the trauma of Knysna.
"Laurent Blanc has done a damn good job," he said enthusiastically.
Although Belgium will be absent from the next European Championship, the technician sees himself very well sharing the plane with the Blue (the French national team)... namely towards Brazil in 2014.
"We little Belgians come out big," he said.
'We're planning one thing, the players are ambitious, they're hungry. '
"You will notice that in the upcoming games." Including the game against France.
Portugal very confident
Paulo Bento's Portugal team looks forward to the return match against Bosnia (22: 00) in Lisbon this Tuesday with great optimism.
In the first leg, both teams lacked objectivity.
'At the end of those 90 minutes we'll be a happy team and, above all, a happy country. '
Paulo Bento already sees himself in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is not the slightest doubt that "La Selecçao," his national team, for which he has been in charge since September 2010, will qualify for the 2012 European Championship.
For Portugal, that means only 90 minutes of bliss.
But there is a match to be played and an opponent to be eliminated, and that is Bosnia.
In view of the game (0-0) on Friday in the hell of Zenica, it seems obvious that the die has not yet been cast.
Portugal dominated the game for more than an hour but were unable to make the all-important mark that would have taken the pressure off them.
'It's a good result but there is some risk because we didn't score an away goal. '
At home, however, at their bright Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced they will prevail in front of a crowd that is likely to be just as keen on the game, even if the match was, of course, announced as "very close," said the upbeat but lucid Bento.
"We expect a very close match but we are totally convinced we can get the better of them," said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
'We still have a 50 per cent chance of being at Euro 2012, 'said Carlos Queiroz's successor.
Friday's draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
A draw may be enough for the Bosnians, who also need a goal.
